{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\n13 Jira issues are pinned at Jira's 5000-comment HARD cap, inflated by the pre-P1\nnon-idempotent re-posting bug (local truth 22-76 distinct comments each; Jira holds ~65\ncopies of each until it hit 5000). P1 (landed a6cdad0e2) STOPS new duplication, but the caps\nremain — so NEW comments on these 13 tickets still silently fail to sync\n(`COMMENTS_PER_ISSUE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED`) until the duplicates are purged.\n\n13 issues (rebar-id -> Jira key, local-distinct / Jira-total): REB-155(5fd2, 76/5000),\nREB-352(e0e2, 64), REB-428(8937, 31), REB-341(db7b, 30), REB-289(b744, 29), REB-427(822a, 27),\nREB-183(7284, 25), REB-327(d251, 25), REB-424(2359, 25), REB-425(33d0, 25), REB-190(75a9, 22),\nREB-426(59ef, 22), REB-453(b4d4, 22).\n\n## Concrete mechanisms (resolve the plan-review blocks — code-grounded, reused not reinvented)\n\n**Bot-authored identification (safety-critical filter).** A comment is bridge-bot-authored IFF\nits raw body contains the reconciler marker `RECONCILER_MARKER = \"<!-- rebar:reconciler-echo -->\"`\n(`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_comments.py:43`), appended to every outbound\ncomment by `_decorate_outbound_comment` (`:140-147`). This intrinsic marker is the PRIMARY and\nauthoritative identifier — robust to accountId / display-name changes, unlike an author field.\nA comment WITHOUT the marker is treated as human/foreign and is NEVER a deletion candidate.\nSecondary cross-check: the backup captures every comment's `author.accountId`; the script\nasserts that all marked (candidate) comments across the 13 tickets resolve to a single bot\n`accountId` and records it — a divergent accountId on a marked comment aborts the run for\nmanual review (defense in depth; the marker still governs).\n\n**Dedup key = the reconciler's OWN normalization (parity guarantee).** Group candidate comments\nby `outbound_comments._normalize_comment_body(body)` — imported and reused verbatim, NOT\nre-implemented — which does ADF->text via `adf.adf_to_text` then strips the marker and\nleading/trailing whitespace (`outbound_comments.py:116-137`). Using the identical function the\nreconciler uses to decide \"already mirrored\" guarantees the cleanup's notion of \"distinct body\"\nmatches the reconciler's, so post-cleanup the reconciler sees exactly one copy per distinct body\nand emits zero re-adds. Machine-canary comments (`_EXCLUDED_COMMENT_PREFIXES`:\n\"BRIDGE_CANARY_ALERT:\", \"Still stale as of\") carry volatile timestamps -> each is a distinct\nnormalized body -> each is kept (never a \"duplicate\" to purge) — correct and safe.\n\n**Pagination (fetch ALL 5000, not the first page).** Reuse the live-validated\n`acli.py::get_comments(key)` with `--paginate` + `_parse_paginated_comments` (the P1 fix,\nconfirmed returning 5000/5000 for REB-155) to build the full comment set for backup + delete-list.\nDo NOT hand-roll a single-page fetch. NOTE: `_parse_paginated_comments` returns only a flat\n`list[dict]` and DISCARDS the response envelope, so it does NOT surface Jira's reported `total`.\nThe completeness check therefore obtains the total via a SEPARATE, dedicated metadata call —\n`GET /rest/api/3/issue/{key}/comment?maxResults=0` returns `{total, maxResults, startAt,\ncomments: []}`; the script reads `total` from that envelope (new script-level work, not provided\nby the reuse target) and reconciles `len(fetched) == total` per ticket, REFUSING to proceed if\nthey differ (guards a silently-truncated fetch producing an incomplete/dangerous delete list).\n\n**Keep-one rule.** For each distinct normalized body among MARKED comments on a ticket: keep the\nOLDEST copy (min `created` timestamp) and delete the rest via\n`DELETE /rest/api/3/issue/{key}/comment/{id}`. A distinct body with only ONE marked copy is\nNEVER deleted. Unmarked (human) comments are never touched.\n\n**Rate limiting + transient-failure handling.** Jira Cloud enforces API rate limits over\n~64k+ DELETEs (≈4900 × 13). Throttle to a conservative default (≤10 req/s, i.e. ≥100ms\ninter-call sleep). IMPORTANT: the existing `_direct_rest_delete` -> `_rest_urlopen_with_retry`\npath does NOT retry HTTP 429/5xx — it re-raises 4xx/5xx immediately as deterministic\n(`acli_rest.py:62-64`), and the only 429+Retry-After logic in the repo lives in\n`dispatch_one._call_with_retry`, which is NOT on the delete path. So the cleanup script MUST\nsupply its own 429/5xx retry wrapper around each DELETE (new script-level work): on HTTP 429 or\n5xx, sleep `Retry-After` (or exponential backoff if absent) and retry up to a bounded count;\nalternatively route `delete_comment` through `dispatch_one._call_with_retry`. Deletions are\nlogged (ticket, comment id, normalized-body hash, outcome) to an append-only artifact as they\nhappen, so a mid-run rate-limit stall is resumable.\n\n**Idempotent + resumable.** Re-running is safe: a comment already deleted (404 on DELETE) is\ntreated as success. On partial failure, re-run `--dry-run` to see the remaining duplicates and\nresume `--execute`; the keep-one grouping is recomputed from the live paginated set each run.\n\n**Rollback (irreversible-op mitigation).** Jira comment deletion cannot be undone via API. The\npre-deletion backup JSON (id, body, author, created, per ticket) is the restore artifact: if a\ncomment must be recovered, re-POST its body to the ticket (note: re-created comments get NEW\nids/timestamps — content-restore, not id-restore). The backup MUST exist and pass its\ncompleteness check before any DELETE fires.\n\n## What — irreversible; execute ONLY under this T4 safety plan (inlined)\n\n- [ ] **Pre-deletion backup:** export FULL comment payload (id, body, author.accountId,\n      author.displayName, created) for all 13 tickets to a versioned JSON artifact under\n      `artifacts/jira-cleanup/backup-<ts>.json` BEFORE any deletion. Proving command: the script\n      asserts, per ticket, `len(backup[key]) == jira_reported_total` and that the artifact is\n      non-empty and parses; deletion is refused if the assertion fails.\n- [ ] **Dry-run default:** the script defaults to `--dry-run`; it prints, per ticket, the count\n      of marked comments, the count of distinct normalized bodies, the kept (oldest) id per body,\n      and the delete-id count — and a machine-readable diff artifact. `--execute` is required to\n      delete and runs ONLY after explicit human approval of the dry-run diff.\n- [ ] **Keep-one dedup:** oldest-`created` kept per distinct normalized body; marker-authored\n      only; single-copy bodies and all unmarked comments excluded (per mechanisms above).\n- [ ] **Operator flow / rejection:** dry-run -> human review -> approve|reject. On reject or\n      abort, NO deletion occurs and the run exits cleanly (backup + dry-run artifacts retained).\n- [ ] **Sequencing:** run ONLY after P1 is live in the reconciler (CONFIRMED: reconcile-bridge\n      run 29625135085 on commit a6cdad0e2 = green) — else the reconciler re-inflates within\n      minutes.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Backup artifact exists and passes its per-ticket completeness check — `len(fetched)` from\n      the paginated `get_comments` equals `total` read from the dedicated\n      `GET /rest/api/3/issue/{key}/comment?maxResults=0` envelope — BEFORE any deletion. Proving\n      command: `python -m json.tool artifacts/jira-cleanup/backup-<ts>.json >/dev/null` + the\n      script's count-reconciliation log line per ticket.\n- [ ] Dry-run diff (delete-id list + kept-oldest-id per distinct body, per ticket) is produced\n      and human-approved before `--execute`. [operator-attested]\n- [ ] Deletion filter provably respects: (a) marked-only (RECONCILER_MARKER present), (b)\n      keep-oldest-per-distinct-body, (c) never single-copy, (d) never unmarked/human. A unit test\n      over a synthetic comment set asserts the delete-list the planner computes matches (a)-(d);\n      RED if the filter mislabels a human/unmarked or single-copy comment as deletable.\n- [ ] Rate-limit safety: DELETE loop throttles and retries 429/5xx with backoff; a unit test\n      asserts a 429 is retried (not dropped) and Retry-After is honored.\n- [ ] Post-execution, each of the 13 tickets is below the 5000 cap AND a reconcile pass emits 0\n      comment re-adds for them (idempotent steady state). [operator-attested against a green\n      reconcile-bridge run]\n- [ ] The deletion log artifact (ticket, comment id, body hash, outcome) exists for the executed\n      run."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784347810057911001,"uuid":"7d5a2de4-a59b-40f9-be68-fb682e25cd6f"}